Project Specification: Sovereign AI Agent Browser Access (2026)
1. Executive Summary
The Problem: Modern travel and airline websites (e.g., United, Delta, Skyscanner) utilize aggressive anti-bot measures such as Cloudflare Turnstile and Akamai. Standard VPS IP addresses and "headless" browsers (Selenium/Playwright) are flagged and blocked instantly. Furthermore, running agents on a primary machine presents an unacceptable security risk to personal data ("Agent Blast Radius").

The Solution: An "Air-Gapped Device Bridge." This architecture uses a physical iPhone (The Body) connected to a Linux Home Server (The Bridge). A Claude agent on a remote VPS (The Brain) controls the iPhone via a private Tailscale network using the Model Context Protocol (MCP). This provides a legitimate residential IP and a 100% human-level mobile browser fingerprint.

2. System Architecture
The Brain (Cloud VPS): Hosts the Claude agent. It performs the reasoning and decision-making.

The Network (Tailscale): A private, encrypted mesh network that connects the VPS to the Home Server without exposing ports to the public internet.

The Bridge (Linux Home Server): A local machine running mobile-mcp and usbmuxd to translate AI commands into hardware actions.

The Body (Physical iPhone): An old iPhone connected via USB to the Linux server. It runs the actual Safari browser or native apps.

3. User Story & Acceptance Criteria
User Story: "As a user, I want my Claude agent to check flight prices using a physical iPhone connected to my home server, so that I can bypass bot detection while keeping my primary data isolated from the agent's environment."

Acceptance Criteria (AC)

AC 1: Secure Connectivity: The VPS agent must successfully ping the Linux Home Server's Tailscale IP.

AC 2: MCP Service: The mobile-mcp server must be active on the Linux host and registered in the agent’s mcp_config.json.

AC 3: Hardware Link: The Linux host must detect the iPhone via USB (verified via lsusb) and maintain an active WebDriverAgent (WDA) session.

AC 4: Vision-Action Loop: The agent must be able to:

Request a screenshot via the get_screenshot tool.

Identify UI elements visually.

Execute a tap(x, y) command on the physical device.

AC 5: Bot Bypass: The agent must be able to complete a full flight search without being flagged as a bot or triggering a CAPTCHA.

4. Implementation Checklist
Phase 1: iPhone Preparation (Requires a Mac)

[ ] Connect iPhone to a Mac and open Xcode.

[ ] Clone the WebDriverAgent (WDA) project.

[ ] Re-sign the WDA app with a personal Apple ID.

[ ] Build and Install WDA onto the iPhone.

[ ] Enable "UI Automation" in the iPhone's Developer Settings.

Phase 2: Linux Home Server Setup

[ ] Connect the iPhone via USB.

[ ] Install usbmuxd and libimobiledevice.

[ ] Install the MCP server: npx -y @mobilenext/mobile-mcp@latest.

[ ] Ensure Tailscale is active and the device is visible to the VPS.

Phase 3: VPS Configuration

[ ] Update mcp_config.json with the Tailscale IP of the home server:
"url": "http://[TAILSCALE-IP]:3000/mcp"

[ ] Test the "Vision Loop" by asking Claude: "Tell me what is currently on my iPhone screen."

5. Alternative Options Evaluated
Option	Status	Reason for Rejection
Personal Laptop	REJECTED	Risk. High "Blast Radius" potential for AI to affect personal files/accounts.
Cloud Sandboxes	REJECTED	Cost/Detection. Expensive per-minute billing and data-center IPs are often flagged.
Qalti (macOS)	REJECTED	Platform Lock. Requires a Mac host and is often tied to proprietary paid APIs.
Open Minis (App)	REJECTED	Limited. Cannot leave the app's internal sandbox to use native iPhone apps.
iPhone Bridge	SELECTED	Sovereign & Stealth. Uses your home IP and real hardware; zero recurring costs.
6. Maintenance & Scalability
Free Tier: The WDA app must be re-signed/re-installed every 7 days using a free Apple Developer account.

Pro Tier: Upgrading to a $99/year Apple Developer account allows the WDA app to remain active for one year without intervention.

Self-Healing: If the connection drops, the VPS agent can use Tailscale SSH to reboot the Linux mobile-mcp service.